"Seattle area friends, I have a very bittersweet announcement that I've been dragging my heels on making: May will be my last month of singing at Bernard's for happy hour. I've met so many cool people, we really built up a beautiful audience, and I'm super proud of my work there, but I just feel like now it's time to move on. I accomplished what I set out to do there (and much more), so it's time to try something new. If you'd like to stop by and say hi before I'm gone, come by today (or any Wednesday in May, probably...) between 5-7 for some cheap booze and live tunes. I'm really going to miss the big 'Mexico' sing-a-longs."

Wonder Wood
2 hrs

Literally just got catcalled in my car by some guy in an 18-wheeler.

My windows arent even down. Were in stop and go traffic; theres not exactly anywhere I can go to escape.

Just. Why.

...

I get that this is the most cliche and normal form of aggression, but I really dont think it should be normal. Im tired of shrugging it off. Im tired of complaining about it and coming up empty for actual solutions.

I recognize that change in a society only happens when every single person takes responsibility for the problem and for changing it. So what can we do? What are steps we can take in the here and now to move toward a future where the entire spectrum of hostility towards women, from catcalling to assaults, is no longer normal?
